				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Strictly speaking, &quot;character-mapped background graphics&quot; means that backgrounds are composed of a grid of references to a dictionary of blocks. I find it strange that someone would be surprised by an NES game being like this, considering that this is how the system itself is designed... NES games don't really have many other options for drawing their graphics, unless they use a lot of dynamically updated CHR-RAM with lots of PRG-ROM to supply new art, but this was anything but feasible back then.<br /><br />Maybe Crane was talking about how the concept was extended to another level, with the use of metatiles, which greatly reduce the memory requirements, but also make the blockiness of the world even more apparent. I don't know what he's comparing SMB to when he says this approach is a step backwards in video game imagery though... it's not like the competition had a lot of memory to work with. Maybe the comparison was against games with small levels, which were more common in the early days of gaming, and didn't need to repeat graphics as much.</div>

